What happens internally when Python executes this code?

a = 10
b = a
a = 20

What will b contain and why?

Explain with reference to memory and object references.


When a = 10 Python creates an integer object 10 in the memory. 
Variable is a references to that object 10 in the memory. 
When b = a Python does not copy the value. b is assigned the same reference as a. 
When a = 20 Python creates a new integer object 20. a now references to the newly created object 20.
b however still references to 10. Therefore the value of b is 10. 
In short python variables store references to object, not the values themselves.
